law.text:
In addition to any other ground that may be applicable under § 21-207 or § 21-209 of this subtitle, a food is adulterated if:
Any part of an important component that normally would be present in the food has been omitted or withdrawn from it;
Any substance has been substituted for any part of an important component that normally would be present in the food;
Any damage to or inferiority of the food has been concealed in any way; or
It has had any substance added, mixed, or packed with it solely for any of the following purposes:
To increase its bulk or weight;
To reduce its quality or strength below that which normally would be expected of the food; or
To mislead the consumer by making the food appear to be better or more valuable than it is.
